tweets.text:
#TeamEA have been out in Ribchester and Billington in #Lancashire today. 

The riverüåämay look calm right now, but things can change quickly.

Make sure you're prepared and sign up now to receive flood alerts and warnings https://t.co/F1wbUHPZe8 https://t.co/KNNgiEuGMD

Our teams continue to work hard to keep communities safe from #flood risk

Keeping watercourses free of blockages, like here at Finchetts Gutter in #Chester, is one of our first line defences to reduce potential #flooding 

Check your local risk: https://t.co/uGQ4g6A5Xn https://t.co/BebPprJfAG

We are expecting rain later today and into tomorrow across the area. 

Please check your flood risk and take action if you are at risk  https://t.co/uGQ4g6RGOV   #Floodaware  #PrepareActSurvive https://t.co/cveq7hjkcL

entity.name: Law & Order: UK
entity.description: In a rare switch for programming usually adapted from one side of the Atlantic to the other, the UK is the recipient this time around. Dick Wolf's long-running US police procedural drama gets a British tweak, as the action shifts from New York to London. Despite the change of scenery, the show's fundamental setup remains comfortably the same: the police investigate a crime in the first half, and the prosecutors go after the offenders in the second half. The only major differences are the accents and white wigs.
